did.unittitle: Lexington-Fayette County (Ky.) Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Web Archives
did.abstract: The Lexington-Fayette County (Ky.) Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Web Archives (dated 2020-2023; 89 online resources: 28 websites, 21 social media sites, 40 blogs) comprises University of Kentucky and Lexington-Fayette County, Kentucky, archived websites and social media pages that document the university and community activities during and responses to the coronavirus disease 2019/COVID-19 pandemic starting in 2020 March and ending in 2023 June.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Collection is open for research at https://archive-it.org/collections/13755.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged into series by type of creator and thereunder by type of online resource.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: 2020ua013 : [identification of item], Lexington-Fayette County (Ky.) Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Web Archives, 2020-2023, University of Kentucky Special Collections Research Center.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Lexington-Fayette County (Ky.) Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Web Archives (dated 2020-2023; 89 online resources: 28 websites, 21 social media sites, 40 blogs) comprises University of Kentucky and Lexington-Fayette County, Kentucky, archived websites and social media pages that document the university and community activities during and responses to the coronavirus disease 2019/COVID-19 pandemic starting in 2020 March and ending in June 2023. Includes only those seeds, Facebook pages, and Twitter and Instagram hashtags that are specifically about the novel coronavirus 2019 or were included as they documented Kentucky's experience with and response to the pandemic. Some social media pages and hashtags have Kentucky-wide content. All other University of Kentucky web content, including all the UKnow press releases referring to the pandemic and the university and UK HealthCare social media accounts, can be found in the University of Kentucky Web Archives. Other community organizations and individuals' online resources that include coronavirus disease 2019 documentation but that are broader in scope than just that topic can be found in the Organizational Records and Community Personal Papers Web Archives collection. All records harvested through Archive-It and Webrecorder. Non-university seeds and social media pages are grouped in Archive-It under Community or Lexington-Fayette Urban County Government.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Property rights reside with the University of Kentucky. The University of Kentucky holds the copyright for materials created in the course of business by University of Kentucky employees. Copyright for all other materials has not been assigned to the University of Kentucky. For information about permission to reproduce or publish, please contact the Special Collections Research Center.

Captured web pages and social media accounts can take a long time to load. Once a page is loaded, for access to embedded audio and video, users may have to click the play button in the Archive-It banner at the top of the page. If a Twitter page does not load but offers the try again button, clicking that button may result in the archived Twitter page functioning correctly.
